&gt; On 11/8/06, Kevin Lawrence &lt;kev.lawrence@...&lt;kev.lawrence%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On 11/7/06, Joseph Shraibman &lt;jks@... &lt;jks%40iname.com&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; to the code it is testing. I&#39;d like to create a junit ant task that
&gt; &gt; &gt; just runs on my whole codebase, but not all of my classes will have
&gt; &gt; &gt; test methods and I&#39;ll get an error for each class that doesn&#39;t (and I
&gt; &gt; &gt; don&#39;t want to have to explictily add each class to my build.xml file
&gt; &gt; &gt; when I add a test).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If I were to try to tackle this, I&#39;d be looking at how the ANT JUnit
&gt; &gt; runner is structured.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Very approximately, it is like this:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;junit&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;test&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;fileset /&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/test&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/junit&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The &lt;junit&gt; task runs all the tests handed to it by one or more &lt;test&gt;
&gt; &gt; elements. The &lt;test&gt; elements get their input from one or more nested
&gt; &gt; &lt;filesets&gt;.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; So rather than having JUnit /not/ filter out the non-tests, I&#39;d have
&gt; &gt; that logic in either a custom subclass of &lt;test&gt; or a custom &lt;fileset&gt;
&gt; &gt; - or maybe even a customer selector within the fileset.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Even if you don&#39;t sprinkle tests throughout your fileset, it&#39;s kinda
&gt; &gt; lame that you have to select tests by doing pattern matching on a
&gt; &gt; .class or .java filename. It&#39;s also error-prone as I have found out
&gt; &gt; way too many times.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I have often wanted to do something similar myself but have never
&gt; &gt; gotten around to it. Let us know how it goes.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Kevin
